SCANSSTAMP(1)                     User Commands                    SCANSTAMP(1)

NAME
    scanstamp - standardize filenames with date prefixes and optional content-derived titles

SYNOPSIS
    scanstamp [OPTIONS] [PATHS]...

DESCRIPTION
    scanstamp is a cross-platform command-line utility that standardizes filenames by
    applying a date prefix and, optionally, generating a human-meaningful document title
    derived from file content.

    The canonical filename format is:

        YYYYMMDD - Document Name.ext

    scanstamp is designed for batch safety, predictable behavior, and full undo support.

OPERATING MODES
    Exactly one mode is active per run. If no mode flag is supplied, smart-title mode is used.

    --date-only
        Add a date prefix only if missing. Never scans content and never calls an LLM.

    --redate
        Replace an existing date prefix if present, otherwise add one. Preserve the title.
        Never scans content and never calls an LLM.

    --keep-title
        Replace or add a date prefix while preserving the title exactly as-is.
        Never scans content and never calls an LLM.

    --keep-date
        Smart-title mode only. Preserve an existing date prefix if present. The title
        may still be replaced by LLM output.

UNDO MODE
    --undo [FILE]
        Reverse previous renames using the log file. If FILE is not supplied,
        .scanstamp-log.csv is used.

        Supports --dry-run.

DATE SELECTION
    Date prefix selection priority:

    1. --date YYYYMMDD
    2. --use-mtime
    3. Today's local date

OPTIONS
    --date YYYYMMDD
        Explicitly set the date prefix.

    --use-mtime
        Use file modification time for the date prefix.

    --prefer-doc-date
        Smart-title mode only. Attempt to parse a date from document content.

    --chars N
        Maximum number of characters used for the content excerpt. Default: 1200.

    --excerpt-mode MODE
        Excerpt extraction strategy. One of:
            firstline
            headings
            firstparas
            raw

    --ocr
        Enable OCR fallback for PDFs using tesseract.

    --recursive
        Recurse into subdirectories.

    --include GLOB
        Include files matching glob. Repeatable.

    --exclude GLOB
        Exclude files matching glob. Repeatable.

    --suffix
        On filename collisions, append (2), (3), etc. instead of skipping.

    --dry-run
        Print proposed changes without renaming files.

    --yes
        Bypass all confirmation prompts.

    --confirm
        Force confirmation prompts even if --yes is not supplied.

    --log FILE
        Write rename log to FILE. Default: .scanstamp-log.csv

    --report FILE
        Write a CSV report of operations to FILE.

    --no-llm
        Disable all LLM usage.

    --local-only
        Do not send any content off-machine.

    --version
        Print version and exit.

    -h, --help
        Show help message and exit.

OUTPUT
    On successful rename:
        Renamed: old.ext -> new.ext

    On dry run:
        DRY RUN: old.ext -> new.ext

    On skip:
        Already dated, skipping: name.ext

    A summary block is always printed at the end of execution.

FILES
    .scanstamp-log.csv
        Default rename log file used for undo operations.

EXIT STATUS
    0   Success
    1   One or more errors occurred

